<DOC><DOCNO> AP890912-0081 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-89 1147EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-HostageAwareness     09-12 0246</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Hostage Awareness,250</SECOND><HEAD>Contest, `Awareness Day' Planned To Honor Hostages</HEAD><BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Congress is being asked to designate journalistTerry Anderson's birthday next month as a national day of prayer forthe eight Americans held hostage in Lebanon.   Rep. Paul Henry, R-Mich., today introduced a joint resolution tomark Oct. 27 as National Hostage Awareness Day. The resolution sayschurch bells should be rung for one minute at noon that day.   Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The AssociatedPress, was kidnapped March 16, 1985, and has been held the longestof any of the eight Americans still believed to be alive.   Anderson will be 42 on Oct. 27.   ``It's ... an exercise in conscience for the American people, sowe can say we did what we could,'' Henry said at a news conference.``This is something we want to have all Americans rally behind.''   Also at the news conference was David Aikman, foreign affairscorrespondent for Time magazine and chairman of the Journalists'Committee to Free Terry Anderson.   Aikman said other activities being planned for Oct. 27 include anationwide essay writing contest for high school students, who willwrite on the subject, ``How I would cope with being a hostage.'' Thewinner will receive $1,000.   The contest and awareness day are intended to keep internationalattention forcused on the hostages as publicity over the presumedmurder of hostage Marine Lt. Col. William Higgins fades, Henry said.</TEXT></DOC>